   321	   clear — set the bit, call its setState in the writer's stack (React
   322	   assigns the writer's lane). Core-effect enqueue rides the same walk;
   323	   `batch()` defers only the core-effect *flush* to close (no implicit
   324	   grouping exists — D10).
   325	6. Writes during render-world evaluation throw (R8); writes in yield gaps
   326	   are ordinary (the fork's callstack truth, F2/I6, classifies them).
   327	
   328	RENDER_NEWEST passes demote to their real (mask, pin) on the first
   329	receipt-creating write *or staged evaluator* (S23) — demotion data is
   330	captured at pass start, so demotion is O(1).
   331	
   332	### 5.2 Visibility (the seed math, verbatim — D3/I15)
   333	
   334	Entry e is visible to world w = (mask, pin p, lockView LV):
   335	
   336	```
   337	visible(e, w) =  (e.retiredSeq ≠ ∅ ∧ e.retiredSeq ≤ p)            // retired by my pin
   338	              ∨ (e.slot ∈ mask ∧ e.seq ≤ p)                       // included, up to my pin
   339	              ∨ (e.slot ∈ LV ∧ e.seq ≤ LV[e.slot].watermark)      // locked into my root
   340	```
   341	
   342	- Pass worlds use the pass's **captured** lock view (immutability is what
   343	  lets a yielded pass keep folding the same world — I34). Fork fact F2
   344	  guarantees no same-root advance can occur while a same-root pass is
   345	  open (a same-root commit discards the WIP pass; React restarts rather
   346	  than resumes — fork test 24 pins this). Cross-root advances re-mint
   347	  *other* roots' views, which this pass never consults.
   348	- committed-for-root(r) worlds use r's **current** view; their worldKey
   349	  includes lockViewId, so every advance re-keys them (no stale
   350	  committed-for-root memo can survive an advance).
   351	- Fold = replay visible entries over base in seq order with stepwise
   352	  equality (I2/I29); reducer ops fold under the world's **effective
   353	  reducer** (staged-in-this-pass else committed — I22/I38). Fold-frame
   354	  callbacks (reducers, equality) run under the I28 guard: signal reads and
   355	  writes throw in all builds.
   356	- `fp(a, w)` and `lockTerm(a, w)` are computed during this same entry scan
   357	  (O(visible entries), no extra pass).
   358	
   359	### 5.3 Retirement (fork F3) and the committed-side order
   360	
   361	Per retiring token t (exactly once, committed flag; async tokens park
   362	until the returned thenable settles — F3/I26):
   363	
   364	1. Within the triggering commit, ordering is fixed (F3/F9 clause, I38c):
   365	   **F9 publications → retirement folds due at this commit → reconcile
   366	   checks and effect flush → layout effects.**
   367	2. Fold: replay t's now-retired receipts into committed truth per §5.2;
   368	   set retiredSeq = ++globalSeq on each entry. **Compaction predicate**
   369	   (normative, both clauses): compaction consumes a **seq-order prefix**
   370	   of the tape — entry e compacts into base iff every entry with seq ≤
   371	   e.seq is retired AND `e.retiredSeq ≤ min(live pins)`. The prefix
   372	   clause preserves replay order (compacting a later ×2 under a pending
   373	   earlier +1 would fold 3 where React commits 4 — C3 row 4); the pin
   374	   clause means every live pin already sees e via the retired clause.
   375	   (The pin-gating is also load-bearing for taint clearing — §6.3.)
   376	3. Mint retireVisStamp(a) for every touched atom; bump
   377	   **committedAdvanceSeq** (L6).
   378	4. Notify committed observers **durably**: enumerate touchedList[slot(t)]
   379	   (never only the consumable write-time queue — I34/S26); reconcile check
   380	   per watcher (compare lastRendered vs the new committed-for-root value;
   381	   setState only on real difference — the value-compare here is committed
   382	   truth, legal per I35's delivery/validity distinction); flush
   383	   useSignalEffects whose snapshot fingerprints moved.
   384	5. Slot bookkeeping: the slot and its touched bits are **retained** until
   385	   its entry count sweeps to zero (I10/I39; entries sweep when compacted).
   386	   Per-root lock records for t clear only after retirement stamps exist
   387	   (injectivity ordering).
   388	6. Store-only batches (no React work) retire through the same path (D2):
   389	   fold, stamps, durable notification — persistence never depends on
   390	   subscription.
   391	
   392	### 5.4 Slot saturation (I39)
   393	
   394	`internSlot` with all 31 slots held (live or unswept): force-clear the
   395	oldest slot k* whose token is fully retired — sweep touchedList[k*]
   396	zeroing bit k* on every listed record; set `fastPathDisabled` on every
   397	live pass whose pin < max retiredSeq of k*'s entries; k*'s entries are
   398	**retained** (retired visibility is slot-free: the retired clause tests
   399	retiredSeq, not slot); wc[k*] zeroes at re-intern; slot generation bumps.
   400	A 32nd *live* token is impossible (fork guarantee, I10), so a fully
   401	retired victim always exists. Forced test: input storm during one yielded
   402	transition (walk C1-X5).
   403	
   404	### 5.5 Quiescence and episodes
   405	
   406	At full quiescence (no live tokens, no live pins, no parked actions):
   407	refresh every K1-touched node holding a committed watcher or effect-dep
   408	snapshot by a K0 NEWEST pull; a node whose refresh twice triggers R8-legal
   409	writes is exempted and its **full reverse-reachable K1 cone** is carried
   410	into the next episode (I42; two-strike rank Σ(2−strikes) terminates a
   411	fixed observed set in ≤2N+1 sweeps). Then: K1 bulk-reset (epoch bump),
   412	plane watermarks reset, counter renumber per the §15 duty list (every
   413	retained stamp rewritten or epoch-guarded — I8). An exemption clears when
   414	a later ordinary K0 NEWEST evaluation of the target completes without
   415	writing.
   416	
   417	## 6. Worlds and read routing
   418	
   419	### 6.1 Read contexts
   420	
   421	- NEWEST (core reads, yield-gap handlers, RENDER_NEWEST passes): K0
   422	  donor-style — pull, recompute if stale. Handlers in yield gaps are
   423	  NEWEST because render-context truth is per-callstack (fork F2, I6/S7).
   424	- Pass worlds and committed-for-root worlds: route per 6.2.
   425	- World evaluations reject writes (R8) and throw on per-world EVALUATING
   426	  re-entry (cycle detection is per-world; K0∪K1 union cycles are legal
   427	  state — I32).
   428	
   429	### 6.2 The fast path and the taint bit (L1 — judge blocker 1 repaired)
   430	
   431	```
   432	fastPath(n, w, pass) =  touched(n) == 0        // no slot bits AND no taint bit
   433	                     ∧  CT(n)                  // cached, zero recompute needed (I12/S9)
   434	                     ∧  ¬stagedFor(n, pass)    // O(1) pass-frame probe (I31)
   435	                     ∧  ¬fastPathDisabled(pass)
   436	```
   437	
   438	else world path: fold atoms per §5.2; consult/evaluate M(n, worldKey);
   439	untracked reads inside world evaluations fold **in-world, edge-free**
   440	(I33's licensed form).
   441	
   442	**The taint bit.** touched bit 31 (TAINT) marks: "this node's K0 cache may
   443	embed pending state that arrived through an untracked read" (I33). Its
   444	complete rule set — all reusing existing machinery:
   445	
   446	- **Set at evaluation (epilogue).** Every K0 NEWEST evaluation of n
   447	  computes a taint input: (a) any untracked read during the evaluation hit
   448	  an atom with a non-empty tape, or hit a computed with `touched ≠ 0`;
   449	  (b) the post-eval dep sweep (rides the existing DEPS_TAIL re-track scan)
   450	  finds TAINT set on any recorded dep. Input true ⇒ set TAINT; false ⇒
   451	  clear TAINT (bit 31 only).
   452	- **Propagate on 0→1.** When TAINT transitions 0→1 on n (by epilogue or by
   453	  inheritance), propagate bit 31 through n's existing out-edges in K0∪K1
   454	  with the same monotone frontier the write walk and edge-add propagation
   455	  already use (`bit & ~touched(m)` — self-terminating, no walkGen needed).
   456	  This is the repair for the judge's blocker: **tracked serves and
   457	  cutoff-clean downstream nodes now inherit taint through the graph**, per
   458	  I17 (path-transitive invariants must propagate through existing
   459	  out-edges), not only at their own evaluations.
   460	- **Tracked reads need no per-read check.** Slot bits reach tracked
   461	  readers through write walks and edge-add propagation; taint reaches them
   462	  through the 0→1 propagation above and the dep sweep. (If the edge is
   463	  created by the reading evaluation itself, edge-add propagation pushes
   464	  the child's current bits — including TAINT — into the reader; both
   465	  link-then-pull and pull-then-link orders are covered.)
   466	- **Clear sites** (I19): the node's own epilogue computing untainted; bulk
   467	  zero at episode reset. Downstream inherited taint out-lives an upstream
   468	  clear until the downstream node's own re-evaluation — conservative,
   469	  never wrong.
   470	- **Cost**: LOGGED-only. One tape/touched check per *untracked* read; one
   471	  bit-AND per dep in the re-track sweep each recompute; propagation only
   472	  on transitions. G-Q/G-W ledger rows (§16).
   473	
   474	### 6.3 TAINT-COMPLETE (the invariant, with its construction)
   475	
   476	**Claim.** If `touched(n) == 0 ∧ CT(n)`, then n's K0 cached value is a
   477	function of committed-visible state only (serving it to any world is at
   478	most *temporal* staleness — the kind untracked licenses — never world
   479	leakage).
   480	
   481	**Base case.** Episode start / DIRECT-era caches: no receipts exist
   482	anywhere; every cache is a function of committed values; all touched
   483	words are zero. ✓
   484	
   485	**Step.** Consider the event that last wrote n's K0 cache (an evaluation
   486	E at NEWEST) and every later event, showing touched(n)=0 survives only if
   487	the property holds:
   488	
   489	- *E's tracked atom reads*: an atom with pending receipts has a non-empty
   490	  tape and slot bits; the edge recorded by E delivers those bits to n
   491	  (write walk if the edge predated the write; edge-add propagation if E
   492	  created the edge). Bits ⇒ touched(n) ≠ 0 — contradiction, so all
   493	  tracked atoms were committed-only. ✓
   494	- *E's tracked computed reads*: by induction the child's cache with
   495	  touched=0 embeds committed-only state; a child with touched ≠ 0 passes
   496	  its bits to n (same two walks) or its TAINT via the dep sweep. ✓
   497	- *E's untracked reads*: epilogue rule (a) sets TAINT for a receipted atom
   498	  or any-bits computed — contradiction; so untracked reads saw
   499	  committed-only state. ✓
   500	- *Events after E*: a later write whose cone reaches n through any
   501	  recorded edge sets a slot bit (write walk / edge-add / E-PRESERVE mirror
   502	  — invariant M, §7.3). A later write reaching n only through an
   503	  untracked-read path cannot change n's *cache* (caches change only at
   504	  evaluations) — it changes what n's evaluation *would* produce; the cache
   505	  still embeds only the old committed values, which is temporal staleness,
   506	  licensed. A later upstream evaluation that embeds pending state into a
   507	  *child's* cache sets the child's TAINT (epilogue), whose 0→1 propagation
   508	  reaches n through the existing edge — even if equality cutoff keeps n
   509	  CLEAN (the cutoff horn; this is exactly the path the round-3 text
   510	  missed). A later retirement only moves state pending→committed
   511	  (never the reverse). ✓
   512	- *Clearing events*: bit s clears only at slot recycle gated on swept
   513	  entries (every pin sees them — §5.3 step 2 makes compaction pin-gated)
   514	  or at saturation force-clear, which compensates by fastPathDisabled on
   515	  every excluded pass (§5.4). TAINT clears only at n's own epilogue, whose
   516	  input freshly re-derives the property; "empty tape" is trustworthy at
   517	  that moment because compaction is pin-gated — a tape can only become
   518	  empty when every live pin already sees its former entries, and every
   519	  future pin is minted above them. Evaluations are stack-atomic (JS), so
   520	  no clear can interleave a half-completed derivation. ∎
   521	
   522	### 6.4 Invariant R (fast-path soundness — full construction)
   523	
   524	**Claim.** The fast path never serves a value that world w's own
   525	evaluation would not produce. Worlds diverge from NEWEST through exactly
   526	four sources (S23's enumeration), each excluded by a conjunct:
   527	
   528	1. **Receipts reachable through recorded topology.** By first-divergence
   529	   (I4), the first divergent atom x is a newest-basis dependency at the
   530	   divergence point and holds a live receipt in slot s; bit s reached n by
   531	   the write walk, edge-add propagation, or the E-PRESERVE mirror (§7.3's
   532	   invariant M), so touched(n) ≠ 0 — refused. Fresh-recompute acquisition
   533	   (S9) is excluded by CT(n): only cached, no-recompute serves are legal
   534	   (I12).
   535	2. **Receipts reachable only through untracked reads.** TAINT-COMPLETE
   536	   (§6.3): an untainted, unbitted, CT cache embeds committed-only state;
   537	   any cache that could embed pending state carries TAINT (set at its
   538	   producing evaluation or inherited through propagation/dep-sweep) —
   539	   refused. World evaluations fold untracked reads in-world, so the
   540	   licensed temporal staleness stays per-world.
   541	3. **Evaluator identity (I22/I31).** A staged evaluator for n exists only
   542	   in its pass's frame; the probe refuses the fast path there, and staging
   543	   demoted RENDER_NEWEST (§5.1). Promotion dirties the K0 node, so
   544	   post-promotion NEWEST reads recompute — CT(n) is false until they do.
   545	4. **Slot-bookkeeping erasure.** Bits clear only at swept-gated recycle
   546	   (I10) or saturation force-clear, which sets fastPathDisabled on every
   547	   pass whose pin the cleared slot's retirement postdates — refused
   548	   wholesale (§5.4).
   549	
   550	Base case: episode start — no receipts, no stages, no taint, all worlds ≡
   551	NEWEST. Step: every event kind's update site is listed above and in the §7
   552	audit table; each preserves its conjunct. ∎
   553	
   554	## 7. K1 and the touched word — one audit table
   555	
   556	### 7.1 K1 plane
   557	
   558	Integer link records (node→node, generation-tagged), add-only within an
   559	episode, bulk-reset at quiescence (§5.5). World evaluations record their
   560	REAL dependencies here (the pending world has a real topology — the D8
   561	answer to I3/S2/S3). K1 records carry lastWalk (walkGen column).
   562	
   563	### 7.2 The touched word — bit audit (the L1 merge's single table)
   564	
   565	| bits | meaning | set by | propagated by | cleared by | forced test |
   566	|---|---|---|---|---|---|
   567	| 0–30 (slot s) | slot s's cone reached n | write walk from written atom | write walk; edge-add propagation (new edge inherits source bits, then delivers retroactively — I23); E-PRESERVE mirrors keep paths alive (§7.3) | slot recycle (swept-gated, I10); saturation force-clear via touchedList sweep (+ fastPathDisabled compensation) | C1 core; C1-X5 |
   568	| 31 (TAINT) | K0 cache may embed untracked-acquired pending state | evaluation epilogue (untracked read hit receipted atom / any-bits computed; dep sweep found tainted dep) | 0→1 transition walks existing out-edges (same monotone frontier) | own epilogue deriving untainted; episode bulk zero | C1-X3 (incl. tracked-serve and cutoff rows) |
   569	
   570	One invariant governs both ranges: **a zero touched word certifies
   571	committed-only content** (TAINT-COMPLETE §6.3 + source 1 of invariant R).
   572	One consumer rule: iterators over slots mask bit 31 (`touched & SLOTS`);
   573	the fast path and the fixup fast-out test the whole word.
   574	
   575	### 7.3 Invariant M (edge knowledge) and E-PRESERVE
   576	
   577	**Invariant M.** At every instant, for every node n and live slot s whose
   578	batch wrote atom x such that some world's evaluation of n read x (directly
   579	or transitively) at or before its pin: bit s ∈ touched(n), OR the edge
   580	path from x to n exists in K0∪K1 and a walk is in progress/queued that
   581	will set it. Maintained at: write time (walk), edge-record time (edge-add
   582	propagation + retroactive per-slot delivery in every non-render context;
   583	queued to the pass's yield/end edge when discovered inside a render
   584	slice), and K0 re-track time (E-PRESERVE strong reading: every edge a K0
   585	re-track removes while any live receipt exists anywhere is mirrored into
   586	K1 with both endpoints and generation). When no receipt exists anywhere, a
   587	dropped edge is safe: resurrecting a displaced branch requires a receipt
   588	on the branching dep, whose write re-records the path (walked at C1-V3).
   589	SP2 (dev validator → CI fuzz gate) brute-force checks M on randomized
   590	retrack schedules.
